    abstract = {{We present a novel formation channel for supermassive black hole (SMBH) binaries in the early Universe, driven by primordial black holes (PBHs). Using high-resolution hydrodynamical simulations, we explore the role of massive PBHs (m$\_{BH}$ {\ensuremath{\sim}} {}10$^{6}$ M$\_{{\ensuremath{\odot}}}$) in catalyzing the formation of direct-collapse black holes (DCBHs), providing a natural in situ pathway for binary SMBH formation. PBHs enhance local overdensities, accelerate structure formation, and exert thermal feedback on the surrounding medium via accretion. Lyman{\textendash}Werner radiation from accreting PBHs suppresses H$\_{2}$ cooling, shifting the dominant gas coolant to atomic hydrogen. When combined with significant baryon{\textendash}dark matter streaming velocities (v$\_{b{\ensuremath{\chi}}}$ {\ensuremath{\gtrsim}} 0.8{\ensuremath{\sigma}}$\_{b{\ensuremath{\chi}}}$, where {\ensuremath{\sigma}}$\_{b{\ensuremath{\chi}}}$ is the rms streaming velocity), these effects facilitate the formation of dense, gravitationally unstable atomically cooling gas clouds in the PBH's wake. These clouds exhibit sustained high inflow rates (Ṁinfall{\ensuremath{\gtrsim}}0.1‑0.01M{\ensuremath{\odot}} yr$^{‑1}$), providing ideal conditions for DCBH formation from rapidly growing supermassive stars of {\ensuremath{\sim}}{}10$^{5}$ M$\_{{\ensuremath{\odot}}}$ at redshift z {\ensuremath{\sim}} 20{\textendash}10. The resulting systems form SMBH binaries with initial mass ratios q{\ensuremath{\sim}}O(0.1) and separations of {\ensuremath{\sim}}10 pc. Such PBH-DCBH binaries provide testable predictions for JWST and Atacama Large Millimeter/submillimeter Array, potentially explaining select high-z sources like little red dots, and represent gravitational-wave sources for future missions like LISA and TianQin{\textemdash}bridging early-Universe black hole physics, multimessenger astronomy, and dark matter theory.}},
